WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.480
Welcome to my talk. Thank you for joining me. I'm going to talk a bit about what I have

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:21.379
been doing in mostly last year. First of all, I started at RStudio a couple of months ago,

00:00:21.379 --> 00:00:34.020
so that's pretty great. I am working on improving a lot of stuff with relation to this, but

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:40.700
this is kind of my last year project. It will probably get some more support on, but right

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:50.660
now it's done kind of stuff. What is gganimate? gganimate is a package

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:58.820
I have wrote. It's kind of a two-fold thing. It's both a grammar of graphics, like a

00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:05.220
theoretical backbone of how to describe animation, and it's also an implementation of said

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:10.500
theoretical backbone. In the same sense that there exists a grammar of graphics theory,

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:15.779
and ggplot2 is just one of many different implementations of this theory, what I wanted

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:21.540
to do with gganimate was also to kind of build a theoretical backbone for how to address

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:28.019
animation and data visualization. It's two-fold, and on top of that, it's an extension to ggplot2,

00:01:28.019 --> 00:01:34.580
so it's not something that exists on its own. It is something that you can apply to any of

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:42.580
your normal ggplot2 plots and make them move magically. Lastly, gganimate is not what it was

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:51.620
a year ago. gganimate actually has a long storied history, starting with years ago,

00:01:52.419 --> 00:01:58.339
David Robinson, who sits down there, wrote gganimate, and he had some other thoughts than

00:01:58.339 --> 00:02:05.540
me about how it should look, and he made it, and it was fantastic, and it got pretty popular,

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:10.339
and at some point he made the big mistake of asking me to take it over, and I had some

00:02:10.339 --> 00:02:19.460
other thoughts. So I rewrote it completely, which also means that if you have code from a

00:02:19.460 --> 00:02:27.940
year ago, I can assure you that it won't run. So I have broken a lot of stuff, but I think I've

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:37.139
done it for good reasons. Furthermore, David never made it to CRAN with his package. I did,

00:02:37.139 --> 00:02:47.699
so it is now on CRAN, and you can grab it from there. And this, of course, is made with gganimate,

00:02:47.699 --> 00:02:53.619
so you can use it to do both serious animation, if such a thing exists, but you can also use it

00:02:54.419 --> 00:03:04.419
to do whatever else you want to play with. So how do I use gganimate? I'm not going to go

00:03:04.419 --> 00:03:09.539
too deep into the theoretical underpinnings of gganimate in this talk. This is more of

00:03:10.419 --> 00:03:15.300
how to get you started doing your first animations, but just to give you a bit of

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:23.940
context, there are at least three quite important parts of the grammar of animations. Probably the

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:29.940
most important part is what's called transitions, or what I've called transitions, which is you have

00:03:29.940 --> 00:03:34.500
some data you wanted to change over the course of the animations, then you need a transition.

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:41.220
There's also something called views, which is you want your view, which is the Y and X scale,

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:45.300
to change during the animation. How do you specify that? And then there's something called

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:50.580
shadows, which is completely different, which is you want the animation to have some sort of memory.

00:03:51.539 --> 00:03:59.860
You might be like, what? Which is fair enough. This is a one-slide overview of the grammar,

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:06.899
so if you want to understand a bit more about the concepts of these, there is a web page,

00:04:06.899 --> 00:04:10.899
gganimate.com, and there's a getting started guide, which kind of holds your hand through

00:04:10.899 --> 00:04:17.619
your first different types of animations and talks a bit about that. Further, I had a presentation

00:04:17.859 --> 00:04:24.339
at Yusr last year, which went into much more detail about my reasons for doing these kind

00:04:24.339 --> 00:04:28.820
of things. So do check them out if you want to understand a bit more about what I'm talking about

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:37.299
right now. So diving headlong into the first example, this is a data set that a lot of people

00:04:37.299 --> 00:04:43.619
are familiar with, and in the context of animation, it's also quite important, because Hans Rosling

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:50.660
became quite famous with presenting exactly this data set. This is an overview of how

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:56.179
different countries have evolved in terms of population, in terms of life expectancies,

00:04:56.179 --> 00:05:04.100
in terms of GDP per capita, and Hans Rosling really showed how animation can be used as great,

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:09.540
great storytelling devices in terms of communicating this data set. So let's play with it a bit.

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:16.260
This is a static version. Of course, if I wanted to make a static plot, this is probably not how

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:24.500
I wanted to do it, but this is kind of our starting point for our animation. We make it as we would

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:29.540
with a ggplot. There's a lot of code up there, but it shouldn't be that problematic. It's standard

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:37.059
ggplot code. And we wind up with this horribly over-plotted scatterplot. So how do we make this

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:46.500
move? Well, it's actually quite simple. Here we want to animate it over year, and year is a

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:53.220
continuous variable, so we use the transition time function, and we give it year and say, well,

00:05:53.220 --> 00:06:02.260
do something with this. And what we get is, wait, it's moving. There's actually a lot of stuff that

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:08.019
happens behind the scene here, because what you're seeing is not only the underlying data,

00:06:08.019 --> 00:06:12.420
but as you can see, it's moving quite smoothly, even though the data doesn't support it.

00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:19.859
gganimate will interpolate your data to ensure that your animation is smooth,

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:29.140
and it will do it in such a way that if I asked for like 10,000 frames for a four-minute animation

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:34.019
of this, it will create enough frames to make it smooth. So it's not something that you do

00:06:34.019 --> 00:06:38.500
up front. You don't have to worry about the length of your animation when you're coding it.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:43.700
It's something that's done when it's rendered. So the specification of the animation is kind

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:51.540
of unitless in that sense. So that's it. That's how you use gganimate. Any questions?

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:58.899
There's, of course, a lot more to it. For instance, if you want this kind of animation,

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:03.380
you don't really have a scale in the same way that you have a scale for your x-axis.

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:09.619
A progress bar would be some sort of scale that allowed you to see where you were in your

00:07:09.619 --> 00:07:14.019
animation. I don't have that yet. I'm looking into it. But one thing you can do is that you

00:07:14.019 --> 00:07:20.179
can change your titles or your labels on your plot. And one way you can do this is that I've

00:07:20.179 --> 00:07:25.779
added support for the glue package, which allows you to insert different variables into your

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:32.660
different titles and labels on your plot. And the different transitions gives you different

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:37.459
variables that you can input, depending on which kind of transitions you have.

00:07:37.459 --> 00:07:43.140
So here we have the frame time. So each frame will actually expose the time that this frame

00:07:43.140 --> 00:07:48.179
is meant to be. And we can see that it updates nicely. And this actually allows for quite a

00:07:48.179 --> 00:07:54.899
powerful way of changing your labels during plotting. I would say that that's the end of

00:07:54.899 --> 00:08:02.260
this animation. But let's try to play a little bit with it. The following animations probably

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:07.779
won't be better, but they will be different. We can add a view to it. Like we talked about,

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:14.739
we can use a view to update the extent of the animation. Here we say we'll use view follow.

00:08:14.739 --> 00:08:21.059
View follow will simply look at the data that is in each frame and just kind of enclose that.

00:08:21.059 --> 00:08:26.420
And I'm setting fixed y to say, well, don't mess with the y-axis. Just update the x-axis

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:32.900
to fit the data in. And we can see that, well, it does that. I would say that these kind of

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:39.859
changing scales are used with care. They should be used with care. They can be quite disorienting.

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:44.979
I don't think that it adds anything positive to this plot, but just to kind of show off

00:08:44.979 --> 00:08:50.500
the views. We can also do other stuff, like the shadows. Shadows were probably the most

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:58.260
part of that slide that you saw, something with memory and all that. It's kind of a weird concept,

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:03.619
but when you see the result, it kind of makes sense. So here we add something called a shadow

00:09:03.619 --> 00:09:10.020
wake, which is something that allows you to trail the old frames in the current frame.

00:09:10.979 --> 00:09:17.539
So what you see here is that we add kind of a trail behind the points. And this is what I mean

00:09:17.539 --> 00:09:25.700
with memory. So what you're seeing is the old data from the previous frames actually being

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:33.380
shown in the current frame. Now, this looks super cutie and not necessarily super important.

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:39.780
There is actually use for such a thing as this. I wouldn't say that it's useful for this. It

00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:45.780
just adds over-plotting. But what these kind of trails can show you is both it can show you some

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:50.020
kind of momentum, how fast are things moving, in which direction are they moving. So they can

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:56.020
actually allow you to better position yourself during the animation. Just to show, beat the

00:09:56.020 --> 00:10:01.140
dead horse, there's other types of shadows. Here's something called shadow mark, which allows you to

00:10:02.580 --> 00:10:08.500
keep raw data points in your animation as the animation progresses. And you can change the

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:14.179
aesthetics of that data point. So as you can potentially see, you can see that a lot of

00:10:14.179 --> 00:10:21.299
points are being left behind as this animation evolves. Again, this is probably not the best

00:10:21.299 --> 00:10:27.059
use case for it. But if you have fewer data points, it can actually allow you to remember where the

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:34.820
different raw data actually was during the animation. OK, new example. This is some

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:39.539
temperature data that I fetched in. Don't look too much at that code. It's just for

00:10:39.539 --> 00:10:44.900
reproducibility. This is just grabbing a lot of temperature measurements in Copenhagen and

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:53.619
Austin to kind of justify why I went here for January. And the static version is just quite

00:10:53.619 --> 00:11:00.340
a similar line graph. And as you can see, it should at least be quite a bit warmer here. So I

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:08.179
made the right choice. So how would I want to animate that? Well, if I wanted to appear for

00:11:08.179 --> 00:11:16.739
one day at a time, you might think, well, days are continuous as well. So let's try transition

00:11:16.739 --> 00:11:21.780
time again. And you will end up with this animation. And you might think that something

00:11:21.780 --> 00:11:29.059
is broken. This is an animation. There's just nothing in there. And you would probably be

00:11:29.380 --> 00:11:38.820
like, what the? But then when you think about it, transition time will cut up your data into

00:11:38.820 --> 00:11:42.739
the different time slots that you have. And you have one measurement per time. And you're

00:11:42.739 --> 00:11:48.099
trying to draw a line with one measurement, which results in no line. So of course, nothing

00:11:48.099 --> 00:11:53.059
gets drawn. And then you might think, wait, there's a use case for shadows, because that

00:11:53.059 --> 00:12:01.780
gives you memory. So we'll add shadow mark, which kind of keeps the old raw data there.

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:10.419
And we get this, which, again, you might be at the point where you say, well, this is really

00:12:10.419 --> 00:12:17.219
a one-trick pony. Can't really do what I want it to do. The thing is that it's actually doing

00:12:17.219 --> 00:12:23.619
what it should be doing. What you might fail to grasp, because it's a quite complicated thing,

00:12:23.619 --> 00:12:30.820
is that, well, shadows don't really combine the old data with the new data. So it is cutting

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:38.340
things up. But it's just, again, drawing a lot of one-point lines here. The shadow data never

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:43.539
connects itself with the old data, for good reasons, because it's not what it's meant to do.

00:12:44.419 --> 00:12:49.940
So what you really want here is another transition, because this is a completely different

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:54.900
way of making animation. And I have a transition just for that, which is the transition reveal.

00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:58.900
And what we see is it's actually doing what we wanted it to do.

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:18.179
And that shouldn't happen. Sorry. Maybe my computer crashed. I'll just try again.

00:13:18.179 --> 00:13:26.419
OK. What this transition also allows you to do is to add other things and lines. And it will

00:13:26.419 --> 00:13:31.859
try to interpret that in a nice sense. So if you add the same data, just as geom points,

00:13:31.859 --> 00:13:38.979
you will, as you probably expect, have a point that traces the frontier of the animation.

00:13:38.979 --> 00:13:43.619
What you don't usually have with geom points is that I'm specifying a group aesthetic here.

00:13:43.619 --> 00:13:48.580
That's not something that you usually do for points. But the group aesthetic in ggAnimate

00:13:48.659 --> 00:13:57.140
has been given an additional purpose in defining the permanence of objects across frames. So you

00:13:57.140 --> 00:14:01.700
need that to say, well, this point is the same, and you need to trace it over.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:14.500
So what happens if it has another really weird? What happens if you give it a unique group?

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:23.299
Well, then it doesn't really get combined across the frames. It will just kind of appear there.

00:14:23.299 --> 00:14:31.059
Lastly, we can do other kinds of visualization here. I do a geom smooth. If you need to

00:14:31.059 --> 00:14:37.299
animate that, you can no longer reference the weekday, because the statistic transformations

00:14:37.299 --> 00:14:41.859
that you've done make the weekday disappear at the moment that you're doing the animation.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:48.419
But in the same way as you can reference statistically computed values during aesthetics,

00:14:48.419 --> 00:14:52.979
you can also do that in transition reveal. And we'll just say, wait until you've done

00:14:52.979 --> 00:14:57.059
the statistics transformation, and then grab the x value that comes out of geom smooth.

00:14:57.059 --> 00:15:06.099
And we can again do this. I'm running low on time, so I'll just jump onto a happy little

00:15:06.099 --> 00:15:14.260
data set of earthquakes. What the? This has nothing to do with the quality of GGAnimate,

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:23.780
I must say. This is purely Keynote's fault. So I've just made a bar plot. And again,

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:31.780
if you want to animate that, we can make the bars appear one month again. This is so weird.

00:15:36.099 --> 00:15:41.219
And we do that with transition states, January, February, and so on. You could consider them

00:15:41.219 --> 00:15:46.179
as continuous variables, but here in the sense that they are ordered factors. So we're using

00:15:46.179 --> 00:15:51.859
a discrete scale, which is transition states. And we add shadow markers we have seen before,

00:15:51.859 --> 00:16:01.299
because we want the old month data to stay there. And we can see we get what we expected.

00:16:01.299 --> 00:16:06.020
What we might think is a bit crude is that they just pop out of nowhere. It's not

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:13.859
nearly as smooth as you might want to have it. And what we can do about this is a new concept

00:16:13.859 --> 00:16:21.140
that I haven't really talked about before, something called entering and exit modifications.

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:27.460
So here we are adding something called enter grow. And this will simply just say when something

00:16:27.619 --> 00:16:39.619
new pops up, let it grow. I'm not going to sing anything now, don't worry. So you can actually

00:16:39.619 --> 00:16:45.619
add flourish like this. And it allows the animation to appear much more smoothly.

00:16:45.619 --> 00:16:54.739
And ggAnimate comes with a number of these different entering and exit transitions,

00:16:54.739 --> 00:17:00.020
or entering and exit modifications. And you can combine them. So you can actually

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:03.780
like enter grow and enter fade, and it will do both of these at the same time.

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:11.780
So you can do quite a lot with the build-in stuff, like so. So I guess this is the last slide.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:17.939
I made it in time. So there will be time for questions while Hadley melts away.

00:17:17.939 --> 00:17:19.939
Thank you for your attention.

00:17:28.660 --> 00:17:32.339
So I think we have time for one question. And then if you have more questions for Thomas,

00:17:32.339 --> 00:17:35.060
he's happy to stay here for the rest of his life.

00:17:37.619 --> 00:17:41.619
Precisely.

00:17:47.939 --> 00:18:01.140
Hey, great talk. Thank you. How does ggAnimate handle gaps in the data? In all of the examples

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:07.380
that you had, you had uniform periods between data. How does it handle something that has

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:08.339
holes in it?

00:18:08.339 --> 00:18:13.859
Well, great question. So I didn't show all the different transitions. There is quite a lot,

00:18:13.859 --> 00:18:18.739
because there's quite a lot of different ways to interpret data in a time sense.

00:18:20.500 --> 00:18:30.819
So with transition time, it kind of looks at the data as key frames. So if some data disappear,

00:18:30.819 --> 00:18:35.939
it will be considered disappearing, and it will be removed. But sometimes you want it

00:18:35.939 --> 00:18:42.260
to kind of just drift over to the next position. Transition component is for when you have these

00:18:42.579 --> 00:18:50.420
non-key frame setups where each element moves based on its own time points. So you can

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:52.979
absolutely do that. I just didn't show it.

